[2026-07-19 18:38:32] [claude-sdk] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01HATggcbjDBT8qXKmy3EP84","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Standard Operating Procedure for New Chapter Activation\n2\t*This guide is a repeatable deployment script. Whenever a new hyper-local sector wants to join the alliance, the local organizers execute these four steps to spin up an autonomous node under the master legal shield.*\n3\t\n4\t> **Activation Pipeline:** [Define Boundary] --> [Select 3-Person Team] --> [Board Resolution] --> [Deploy Sub-Ledger]\n5\t\n6\t### Step 1: Define the Hyper-Local Boundary\n7\tThe incoming \"Link\" must be defined entirely by its residents. The recommended scale is one central block (the section between the two closest cross streets) plus 2 to 4 immediately adjacent blocks (a 3-to-5-block cluster). This keeps the psychological footprint small, hyper-local, and highly manageable.\n8\t\n9\t### Step 2: Nominate the 3-Person Stewardship Team\n10\tTo keep administration lean and avoid top-heavy boards, each Link is anchored by three specific resident volunteer roles:\n11\t* **The Router (Communications):** Manages local messaging channels, digital invites, porch-to-porch welcome outreach, and cross-neighborhood promotion for [Community Clubs](file:///c:/Users/donno/source/mneighbor-alliance/COMMUNITY_CLUBS.md).\n12\t* **The Ledger (Finance):** Manages the local micro-pool of funds, tracks neighborhood contributions, and coordinates reimbursements.\n13\t* **The Protocol (Logistics):** Holds the master copy of the permitting guide, builds the maps, and coordinates the city insurance certificates.\n14\t\n15\t### Step 3: Execute the Board Charter Resolution\n16\tThe new neighborhood does not file paperwork with the government. Instead, the master MNeighbor Alliance board passes a single-sentence corporate resolution:\n17\t> *\"The board officially recognizes and establishes the '[Neighborhood Name] Link' as an official internal chapter of MNeighbor Alliance, granting it full access to the corporate liability shield, master insurance coverage, and open-source toolkits.\"*\n18\t\n19\t### Step 4: Configure the Sub-Ledger\n20\tThe master MNA bank account remains a single repository, but the master treasurer configures an isolated tracking sub-ledger for the new Link. All funds contributed by neighbors within that specific boundary are tagged exclusively for their local events.\n21\t\n22\t---\n23\t\n24\t### 🌐 The Track B Alternative: The Affiliate MOU\n25\tIf an adjacent neighborhood block is already hyper-organized and possesses its own independent non-profit status (e.g., a localized community council like LexHam), do not use the steps above. Instead, execute the Affiliate Memorandum of Understanding (MOU):\n26\t* **Fiduciary Firebreak:** The MOU explicitly dictates that both organizations remain entirely independent legal entities. Neither assumes financial or legal liability for the actions, debts, or omissions of the other.\n27\t* **Asset Interoperability:** Both groups agree to cross-promote events, coordinate street-closure calendars to avoid scheduling conflicts, and share non-monetary physical assets (e.g., traffic sawhorses, canopies, or tech gear).\n28\t* **The Mesh Council:** The affiliate group appoints one volunteer \"Router\" to sit on a bi-annual peer-to-peer roundtable to maintain an open communication mesh across neighborhoods, including cross-promoting interest groups and community clubs.\n29\t\n30\t> 📝 **Template Filling Note:** When utilizing templates located within the `/templates` folder (such as the Affiliate MOU), ensure all localized variables inside brackets `[ ]` are modified to reflect your node configuration details prior to routing or formal signatures.\n31\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"393aa51d-281a-4b41-acea-1abc9b5cff0a","uuid":"9ec0edb9-8d59-4c2a-bb3b-ebce4c0c2660","timestamp":"2026-07-19T23:38:31.721Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/c/Users/donno/source/mneighbor-alliance/NEIGHBOR_LINK_ONBOARDING.md","content":"# Standard Operating Procedure for New Chapter Activation\n*This guide is a repeatable deployment script. Whenever a new hyper-local sector wants to join the alliance, the local organizers execute these four steps to spin up an autonomous node under the master legal shield.*\n\n> **Activation Pipeline:** [Define Boundary] --> [Select 3-Person Team] --> [Board Resolution] --> [Deploy Sub-Ledger]\n\n### Step 1: Define the Hyper-Local Boundary\nThe incoming \"Link\" must be defined entirely by its residents. The recommended scale is one central block (the section between the two closest cross streets) plus 2 to 4 immediately adjacent blocks (a 3-to-5-block cluster). This keeps the psychological footprint small, hyper-local, and highly manageable.\n\n### Step 2: Nominate the 3-Person Stewardship Team\nTo keep administration lean and avoid top-heavy boards, each Link is anchored by three specific resident volunteer roles:\n* **The Router (Communications):** Manages local messaging channels, digital invites, porch-to-porch welcome outreach, and cross-neighborhood promotion for [Community Clubs](file:///c:/Users/donno/source/mneighbor-alliance/COMMUNITY_CLUBS.md).\n* **The Ledger (Finance):** Manages the local micro-pool of funds, tracks neighborhood contributions, and coordinates reimbursements.\n* **The Protocol (Logistics):** Holds the master copy of the permitting guide, builds the maps, and coordinates the city insurance certificates.\n\n### Step 3: Execute the Board Charter Resolution\nThe new neighborhood does not file paperwork with the government. Instead, the master MNeighbor Alliance board passes a single-sentence corporate resolution:\n> *\"The board officially recognizes and establishes the '[Neighborhood Name] Link' as an official internal chapter of MNeighbor Alliance, granting it full access to the corporate liability shield, master insurance coverage, and open-source toolkits.\"*\n\n### Step 4: Configure the Sub-Ledger\nThe master MNA bank account remains a single repository, but the master treasurer configures an isolated tracking sub-ledger for the new Link. All funds contributed by neighbors within that specific boundary are tagged exclusively for their local events.\n\n---\n\n### 🌐 The Track B Alternative: The Affiliate MOU\nIf an adjacent neighborhood block is already hyper-organized and possesses its own independent non-profit status (e.g., a localized community council like LexHam), do not use the steps above. Instead, execute the Affiliate Memorandum of Understanding (MOU):\n* **Fiduciary Firebreak:** The MOU explicitly dictates that both organizations remain entirely independent legal entities. Neither assumes financial or legal liability for the actions, debts, or omissions of the other.\n* **Asset Interoperability:** Both groups agree to cross-promote events, coordinate street-closure calendars to avoid scheduling conflicts, and share non-monetary physical assets (e.g., traffic sawhorses, canopies, or tech gear).\n* **The Mesh Council:** The affiliate group appoints one volunteer \"Router\" to sit on a bi-annual peer-to-peer roundtable to maintain an open communication mesh across neighborhoods, including cross-promoting interest groups and community clubs.\n\n> 📝 **Template Filling Note:** When utilizing templates located within the `/templates` folder (such as the Affiliate MOU), ensure all localized variables inside brackets `[ ]` are modified to reflect your node configuration details prior to routing or formal signatures.\n","numLines":31,"startLine":1,"totalLines":31}}}
